      <!--exercises 3 - 6 in OG graph transformations -->
      <exercisegroup cols="2">
        <introduction>
          <p>
            First write <m>g(x)</m> in terms of <m>f</m>. Then compose a sequence of transformations that will transform the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> into the graph of <m>y=g(x)</m>.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <!--exercises 3 in OG graph transformations -->
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>f(x)=\sqrt{x}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
              <m>g(x)=\frac{\sqrt{x-7}}{4}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <md>
                <mrow> g(x) \amp = \frac{\sqrt{x-7}}{4} </mrow>
                <mrow>  \amp = \frac{1}{4}\sqrt{x-7} </mrow>
                <mrow>  \amp = \frac{1}{4}f(x-7) </mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
            <p>
              So we can transform <m>y=f(x)</m> into <m>y=g(x)</m> by first shifting right <m>7</m> units and then compressing vertically by a factor of <m>\frac{1}{4}</m>. (There are other correct answers.)
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
        <!--exercises 4 in OG graph transformations -->
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>f(x)=\frac{1}{x}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
              <m>g(x)=\frac{2}{x}+3</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <md>
                <mrow> g(x) \amp = \frac{2}{x}+3 </mrow>
                <mrow>  \amp = 2 \cdot \frac{1}{x}+3 </mrow>
                <mrow>  \amp = 2f(x)+3 </mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
            <p>
              So we can transform <m>y=f(x)</m> into <m>y=g(x)</m> by first stretching vertically by a factor of <m>2</m> and then shifting up <m>3</m> units. (There are other correct answers.)
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
        <!--exercises 5 in OG graph transformations -->
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>f(x)=x^2</m>
            </p>
            <p>
              <m>g(x)=-4\left( \frac{1}{2}x-5 \right)^2+3</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <md>
                <mrow> g(x) \amp =-4\left( \frac{1}{2}x-5 \right)^2+3 </mrow>
                <mrow>  \amp = -4f\left( \frac{1}{2}x-5 \right)+3 </mrow>
                <mrow>  \amp = -4f\left( \frac{1}{2} \left(x-10 \right) \right)+3 </mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
            <p>
              So we can transform <m>y=f(x)</m> into <m>y=g(x)</m> by first stretching horizontally by a factor of <m>2</m> and then shifting right <m>10</m> units. Then, stretching vertically by a factor of <m>4</m> and reflecting across the <m>x</m>-axis, and finally shifting up <m>3</m> units. (There are other correct answers.)
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
        <!--exercises 6 in OG graph transformations -->
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>f(x)=\sqrt[3]{x}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
              <m>g(x)=\frac{1}{2}\sqrt[3]{10x+30}-6</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <md>
                <mrow> g(x) \amp =\frac{1}{2}\sqrt[3]{10x+30}-6 </mrow>
                <mrow>  \amp = =\frac{1}{2}f(10x+30)-6 </mrow>
                <mrow>  \amp = =\frac{1}{2}f\left( 10\left( x+3 \right) \right) -6 </mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
            <p>
              So we can transform <m>y=f(x)</m> into <m>y=g(x)</m> by first compressing horizontally by a factor of <m>\frac{1}{10}</m> and then shifting left <m>3</m> units. Then, compressing vertically by a factor of <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> and finally shifting down <m>6</m> units. (There are other correct answers.)
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
